        <section id="overview">
            <h2>Understanding Your Funding Options</h2>
            <p>Paying for college can seem overwhelming, but there are many resources available to help you afford your education. This guide will walk you through the main funding sources available to students, including federal financial aid (FAFSA) and specialized support through the Department of Rehabilitation (DOR).</p>
            
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <h3>ðŸ“º Watch: Complete Overview of Funding Sources</h3>
                <p>This comprehensive video explains all the different ways to pay for college, including grants, scholarships, work-study, and loans. Understanding these options is the first step to making college affordable.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="video-container">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/M4XWGZ87GHA" allowfullscreen allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"></iframe>
            </div>

            <div class="info-box">
                <h3>Key Takeaways from the Video:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Grants:</strong> Free money you don't have to pay back (Pell Grant, Cal Grant, etc.)</li>
                    <li><strong>Scholarships:</strong> Merit or need-based awards that don't require repayment</li>
                    <li><strong>Work-Study:</strong> Part-time jobs to help pay for school</li>
                    <li><strong>Federal Loans:</strong> Low-interest loans that must be repaid after graduation</li>
                    <li><strong>DOR Services:</strong> Support for students with disabilities</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="fafsa">
            <h2>FAFSA - Free Application for Federal Student Aid</h2>
            
            <div class="info-box">
                <h3>What is FAFSA?</h3>
                <p>The Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA) is the key to accessing federal financial aid for college, including grants, work-study programs, and federal student loans. Completing the FAFSA is essential for any student planning to attend college, as most colleges and states also use it to determine eligibility for their own financial aid programs.</p>
            </div>

            <h3>Why Complete the FAFSA?</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Access federal grants (money you don't have to pay back)</li>
                <li>Qualify for federal student loans with low interest rates</li>
                <li>Be considered for work-study programs</li>
                <li>Many colleges and states require it for their own aid programs</li>
                <li>It's free to complete!</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Important Deadlines</h3>
            <div class="info-box">
                <p><strong>Federal Deadline:</strong> June 30 of each award year</p>
                <p><strong>California State Deadline:</strong> March 2 (priority deadline for Cal Grant consideration)</p>
                <p><strong>Note:</strong> Many colleges have earlier deadlines. Check with your specific schools!</p>
            </div>

            <h3>Documents You'll Need</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Social Security number (and parents' if dependent student)</li>
                <li>Federal tax returns (yours and parents' if dependent)</li>
                <li>W-2 forms and other earnings records</li>
                <li>Bank statements and investment records</li>
                <li>Records of untaxed income</li>
                <li>FSA ID (create one at studentaid.gov)</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>How to Complete the FAFSA</h3>
            <p>Access helpful resources to guide you through the FAFSA process:</p>
            
            <div class="info-box">
                <p><strong>Official Federal Student Aid YouTube Channel:</strong> Watch step-by-step FAFSA tutorials and helpful videos from the U.S. Department of Education.</p>
                <a href="https://www.youtube.com/@FederalStudentAid" class="btn" target="_blank">Watch FAFSA Video Tutorials on YouTube</a>
                
                <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem;"><strong>Complete Your FAFSA:</strong> Start your FAFSA application online.</p>
                <a href="https://studentaid.gov/h/apply-for-aid/fafsa" class="btn" target="_blank">Start Your FAFSA</a>
                
                <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem;"><strong>FAFSA Help and Resources:</strong> Get answers to common questions and find additional support.</p>
                <a href="https://studentaid.gov/" class="btn" target="_blank">Visit Federal Student Aid Website</a>
            </div>

            <h3>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Missing the deadline - submit as early as possible!</li>
                <li>Not listing all schools you're considering</li>
                <li>Using incorrect or outdated tax information</li>
                <li>Skipping questions - complete every section</li>
                <li>Not signing and submitting the form</li>
            </ul>

            <a href="https://studentaid.gov/h/apply-for-aid/fafsa" class="btn" target="_blank">Complete FAFSA Online</a>
            <a href="https://studentaid.gov/" class="btn" target="_blank">Federal Student Aid Website</a>
        </section>

        <section id="dor">
            <h2>Department of Rehabilitation (DOR) Services</h2>
            
            <div class="info-box">
                <h3>What is DOR?</h3>
                <p>The California Department of Rehabilitation (DOR) helps people with disabilities obtain and retain employment and maximize their ability to live independently. DOR provides educational funding for trade schools, community colleges, and universities to eligible students.</p>
            </div>

            <h3>Who Qualifies?</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>California residents with physical or mental disabilities</li>
                <li>The disability results in a substantial impediment to employment</li>
                <li>Vocational rehabilitation services are required to prepare for, enter, or retain employment</li>
                <li>The individual can benefit from vocational rehabilitation services</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Educational Support Covered</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Trade Schools:</strong> Vocational and technical training programs</li>
                <li><strong>Community Colleges:</strong> Associate degree and certificate programs</li>
                <li><strong>Universities:</strong> Bachelor's and advanced degree programs</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Services DOR Can Provide</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Tuition and fees for approved educational programs</li>
                <li>Books and supplies</li>
                <li>Transportation assistance</li>
                <li>Assistive technology and accommodations</li>
                <li>Career counseling and guidance</li>
                <li>Job placement assistance</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Required Forms</h3>
            <p>To apply for DOR services, you'll need to complete the following forms:</p>
            
            <div class="info-box">
                <p><strong>DR 260:</strong> Application for Vocational Rehabilitation Services</p>
                <a href="https://www.dor.ca.gov/Home/Forms" class="btn" target="_blank">Download DR 260</a>
                
                <p style="margin-top: 1rem;"><strong>DR 222:</strong> Authorization for Release of Information</p>
                <a href="https://www.dor.ca.gov/Home/Forms" class="btn" target="_blank">Download DR 222</a>
            </div>

            <h3>How to Apply</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Complete the DR 260 application form</li>
                <li>Complete the DR 222 release of information form</li>
                <li>Gather documentation of your disability (medical records, IEP, etc.)</li>
                <li>Submit forms to your local DOR office</li>
                <li>Attend an intake appointment with a DOR counselor</li>
                <li>Work with your counselor to develop an Individualized Plan for Employment (IPE)</li>
            </ol>

            <a href="https://www.dor.ca.gov/" class="btn" target="_blank">Visit California DOR Website</a>
            <a href="https://www.dor.ca.gov/Home/FindAnOffice" class="btn" target="_blank">Find Your Local DOR Office</a>
        </section>

        <section id="scholarships">
            <h2>Additional Funding: Scholarships</h2>
            <p>Beyond FAFSA and DOR, scholarships are an excellent way to fund your education. Scholarships are essentially "free money" that you don't have to pay back.</p>
            
            <div class="info-box">
                <h3>Types of Scholarships:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Merit-based:</strong> Based on academic, athletic, or artistic achievement</li>
                    <li><strong>Need-based:</strong> Based on financial need</li>
                    <li><strong>Identity-based:</strong> For specific groups (first-generation, minorities, etc.)</li>
                    <li><strong>Field-specific:</strong> For students pursuing particular majors or careers</li>
                    <li><strong>Local scholarships:</strong> From community organizations and local businesses</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <a href="scholarships.html" class="btn">Explore Scholarship Opportunities</a>
        </section>

